# Keeper Platform Development Rules (v2 --- August 2025)

This document is the **canonical, in-repo source of truth** for Keeper
development.\
It supersedes all prior versions (including v1).\
Cursor and all developers must follow this file when contributing to the
Keeper Platform.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 1) Architecture & Repo Conventions

-   **Monorepo** (pnpm workspaces) with dual targets: **React Frontend
    (Vite, deployed on Vercel)** and **Express Backend (Railway)**.
-   Expected workspace layout (names may vary; adjust as needed):
    -   `apps/web` -- React + Vite app for Vercel. Entry:
        `src/main.tsx`. JSX/TSX in `src/**/*.tsx`.
    -   `apps/api` -- Express server for Railway. Entry: `src/index.ts`.
        Routes in `src/routes/**`, services in `src/services/**`.
    -   `packages/*` -- shared libs (types, ui, utils). Publish config
        private.
-   **Package manager:** pnpm. Use `pnpm -w` at repo root for workspace
    ops.
-   **Node target:** 20.x LTS.

## 2) Technologies

-   **Frontend:** React, Vite, TypeScript, Tailwind, shadcn/ui,
    lucide-react, framer-motion (as needed). Routing via
    react-router-dom (unless otherwise specified).
-   **Backend:** Express, TypeScript (`tsx`/ts-node for dev), Prisma ORM
    to **Postgres** (Railway). Redis is **optional** (see §7).
-   **Auth:** KAM (Keeper Access Module) provides JWT-based auth &
    settings management.
-   **Theming:** Dynamic theming via MediaFrame/Theme models; default
    **Keeper Classic** present after resets.

## 3) Environments & Deployment

-   **Vercel** for `apps/web` (monorepo aware). Use `VERCEL_PROJECT_ID`
    and build from workspace.
-   **Railway** for `apps/api`. Environment variables managed in
    Railway.
-   **Branching:** `main` (protected). Feature branches: `feat/*`,
    fixes: `fix/*`, chores: `chore/*`.
-   **Releases:** Tag `vX.Y.Z`. Production deploys from tags or `main`
    with CI confirmation.

## 4) Database & Migrations (Prisma + Postgres)

-   Prisma schema: `apps/api/prisma/schema.prisma`.
-   Commands:
    -   Dev: `pnpm --filter keeper-api prisma:generate` then `dev`.
    -   Migrate: `pnpm --filter keeper-api prisma:migrate:dev` (local),
        `prisma:migrate:deploy` (prod).
-   **Seeders:** idempotent; ensure themes (Keeper Classic, Keen Kip,
    Lowcountry Summer, Juke Joint) are re-added after resets.

## 5) Environment Variables (Backend)

-   `DATABASE_URL` (required)
-   `REDIS_URL` (optional; see §7)
-   `DISABLE_REDIS` (set to `true` to bypass Redis at runtime & in dev)
-   `JWT_SECRET` (required)
-   `NODE_ENV` (optional, defaults to `development`)
-   Any provider keys (OpenAI, Together, ElevenLabs) **must not** be
    hardcoded; use env + server-side access only.

## 6) TypeScript, Build & Module Rules

-   **TSConfig:** ESM (NodeNext) or CommonJS---pick one per target and
    be consistent. If ESM on backend, **avoid default import pitfalls**
    with libraries like `ioredis`.
-   **Strict:** `strict: true`, no `any` leakage. Fix `unknown`
    accesses.
-   **Paths:** Use `tsconfig` path aliases; Vite + tsconfig-paths plugin
    on frontend; tsconfig-paths in Node if needed.
-   **Outputs:** Frontend: Vite build to `dist`. Backend: tsc output to
    `dist` or run with `tsx` in dev.

## 7) Redis Policy (Optional Cache/Queue)

-   Backend must run without Redis. If `REDIS_URL` missing, code must
    **respect `DISABLE_REDIS=true`** and stub adapters.
-   Any Redis client wrapper must throw **clear errors** if enabled but
    misconfigured.

## 8) Coding Standards

-   **Linting:** ESLint + TypeScript plugin across workspaces.
-   **Formatting:** Prettier. One configuration at repo root.
-   **Commits:** Conventional Commits (e.g., `feat:`, `fix:`, `chore:`).
-   **Tests:** Vitest/Jest (unit), Playwright (e2e where relevant).
    Minimum coverage targets by module as we mature.

## 9) Error Handling & Logging

-   **Backend:** Structured logs (pino or console JSON). Include
    `requestId`. Do not log secrets.
-   **Frontend:** Error boundaries around route roots; user-friendly
    toasts; Sentry (optional) behind env flag.

## 10) Security & KAM (Keeper Access Module)

-   **KAM** governs access policies (roles, domains, sharing). API
    routes must check KAM before returning private data.
-   CORS is **domain-aware** (Domains act as permission/sharing
    controllers). Avoid wildcard `*` in prod.
-   Never expose secrets to client; use server endpoints.

## 11) UX Principles

-   **Mobile-first**. Performance budget enforced.
-   **Boards/Frames:** Dialog, Topics, Drafts, Tasks, Config, Activity.
    MemoryFrame is nice-to-have, not MVP-blocking.
-   **Studio:** Capture → Connect → Create → Build arc; maintain
    consistent theming.

## 12) AI & Kip

-   Kip (Keeper Interface Protocol) is **framework**, not persona.
    Agents are modular. Keep MCP endpoints clean.
-   RAG + fine-tune hybrid planned. Keep embeddings/data layers behind
    server.

## 13) CI/CD

-   CI validates: install, typecheck, lint, test, build (web+api).
-   CD deploys web to Vercel & api to Railway on tags/approved main
    merges.

## 14) Git/GitHub Workflow

-   Small PRs. Include **Checklist** (see §16). Link issues. Screenshots
    for UI changes. Schema diffs for DB changes.
-   Require at least 1 review. No direct pushes to `main`.

## 15) Definition of Done (DoD)

-   Builds locally for both targets.
-   CI passing (typecheck/lint/tests/build).
-   Docs updated (README, .env.example, CHANGELOG if user-visible).
-   Observability hooks in place (logs, basic metrics if applicable).

## 16) PR Checklist (paste into PRs)

-   [ ] Clarifies scope & acceptance criteria
-   [ ] Touches only one logical concern
-   [ ] Typechecks & lints cleanly
-   [ ] Unit tests updated/added
-   [ ] DB migration safe & reversible
-   [ ] Feature flagged (if risky)
-   [ ] Web build OK (Vercel)
-   [ ] API build OK (Railway)
-   [ ] Docs updated (README/.env.example)
-   [ ] Screens/recording added (UI)

## 17) Release & Rollback

-   Tag semantic version. Maintain CHANGELOG.
-   Rollback plan: revert tag or redeploy previous artifact. For DB,
    apply down migrations only if safe.

